*new seagrass fixture shades (60.00) @amazon⁣
*antique door knob for the towel holder ⁣
*styled with stuff I already had ⁣

The rest was a lot of walking,beaching and eating! Some shopping on Boxing Day too so not a complete change up😉 ⁣
We also took in the markets in funky Fremantle and a tour of the very old prison there. A highlight! ⁣
⁣
WA🥰 Put in on your Australia travel list! ⁣

Simple Asian Dumpling Soup:⁣
2 servings ( I doubled ) ⁣
⁣
•10-12 veggie chicken pork beef or shrimp dumplings. Fresh or frozen ⁣
•4 cups chicken or vegetable stock ⁣
•2 tsp finely chopped ginger ⁣
•1 lg garlic  clove chopped ⁣
•1 tsp sesame oil⁣
•1/2 cup grated carrot⁣
•4 lg shiitake mushrooms chopped ⁣
•1 1/2 cups sun Chou ( Chinese cabbage) or baby bok choy( I did both!) chopped ⁣
•1 green onion thinly sliced ⁣
•fresh cilantro to taste ⁣
•hot Asian-style chilli sauce to taste ⁣
⁣
Pour 8 cups of water into an 8 inch wide pot, set over medium heat, and bring to a gentle simmer. Meanwhile, place stock, ginger, garlic, sesame, oil, carrots, and mushrooms in a second pot, and set it aside for now.⁣
⁣
When the water is gently simmering, add the frozen dumplings. Return to a gentle simmer simmer dumplings, for five minutes or until cooked through, and the dumpling wrappers look a tiny bit translucent where the filling is. ⁣
While the dumplings cook, set the pot with the stock mixture in it over medium high heat, and bring to a simmer. Add the Sun choy⁣
and /or baby bok choy to the stock mixture, and then turn the heat to medium low.⁣
⁣
When cooked lift the dumplings out of the water and divide them between two large soup bowls. Divide and ladle some of the stock mixture into each bowl. Sprinkle soups with green onions and cilantro. Serve with soy sauce and hot chilli sauce at the table.⁣
Enjoy!

CORN SHUCKING HACK! Save this for your next corn feed.🤯 🌽 ⁣
⁣
**Note, please don’t comment on the use of the microwave. I’m not a scientist,  I’m not a chef, but I’m totally OK with using a microwave once in a while.🤷🏻‍♀️⁣
⁣
How to: ⁣
Try this when you’re cooking a couple of cobs . ⁣
Put them in the microwave for four minutes husk on. ⁣
Cut the end of the corn off - handle carefully as it will be hot. ⁣
Then gently squeeze the corn out holding onto the tip end. The silk will stay with the husk and voila! cooked shucked corn.⁣
⁣
Let me know if you try it!!⁣

Italian Wedding Soup : ⁣
4 tbsp evoo ⁣
1 1/3 cup yellow onion ⁣
2/3 cup chopped carrot + celery⁣
2 tbsp minced garlic⁣
6 cups unsalted chicken broth ⁣
6 oz orzo pasta ⁣
1 1/2 tbsp fresh oregano ⁣
1/2 teaspoon kosher salt ⁣
24 cooked chicken  meatballs ( fresh homemade or frozen ) ⁣
4 cups baby spinach ⁣
1/4 cup Parmesan cheese⁣
⁣
1. Heat oil in a large pot or Dutch oven over medium high heat. Add onion, carrots, celery, and garlic; cook, stirring occasionally until onion is translucent.⁣
2. Add broth, cover, and bring to a boil. Add orzo, oregano and salt; cover and cook, stirring occasionally, until orzo is just tender about nine minutes.⁣
3. Stir in meatballs and spinach; cook until the meatballs are heated through, and the spinach is wilted 2 to 4 minutes.⁣
4. Serve hot, sprinkled with Parmesan cheese⁣

Veggie Miso Ramen: serves 4 large bowls

8 cups low sodium vegetable broth (or pho or chicken!)
2  3” square pieces of kombo ( dried kelp) or dried seaweed
10 small shiitake mushrooms 
4 garlic cloves chopped 
2 tbsp ginger (fresh chopped or jar)
4 tbsp ea: sesame seeds, sugar, soy sauce, sesame oil
4 tbsp shiro ( white ) miso
bunch bok choy chopped
600 grams ramen - fresh or dried - I used rice noodles!
2 medium soft boiled eggs ( aim for alittle runny - I failed!)
4 green onions chopped 
fresh bean sprouts to taste 
Sriracha chill sauce to taste
